
[1]ceremonial

   CEREMONIAL, a. [See Ceremony.]

   1. Relating to ceremony, or external rite; ritual; according to the
   forms of established rites; as ceremonial exactness. It is particularly
   applied to the forms and rites of the Jewish religion; as the
   ceremonial law or worship, as distinguished from the moral and judicial
   law.

   2. Formal; observant of old forms; exact; precise in manners.

   [In this sense, ceremonious is now used.]

                               CEREMONIAL, n.

   1. Outward form; external rite, or established forms or rites,
   including all the forms prescribed; a system of rules and ceremonies,
   enjoined by law or established by custom, whether in religious worship,
   in social intercourse, or in the courts of princes.

   2. The order for rites and forms in the Romish church, or the book
   containing the rules prescribed to be observed on solemn occasions.
